 <details>
   <summary>About the commit history</summary>
   <p>The original commits from the main repository are not preserved when code is copied to this repository because they contain references to files that don't exist in this repository. So, the Cardinal CI bot will create new commits that contain changes for only the files that are published to the self-hosted repository.</p>
-  <p>Unfortuntely, this process results in losing the original commit messages. The commits in this repository are also less granular, containing everything from the last merge to main upstream in a single commit.</p>
+  <p>Unfortuntely, this process results in losing the original commit messages. The commits in this repository are also less granular, with each commit each containing everything from the last merge to main upstream.</p>
+  <p>I recognize the issues that this will create for contributors. The CI job responsible for publishing this code is located at <code>./github/workflows/publish-oss.yaml</code> and I would accept updates that make this repo more useful.</p>
 </details>
 
 <details>
   <summary>How do I build the apps?</summary>
-  <p>The official builds that are on <a href="https://hub.docker.com/r/cardinalapps/media-server">Docker Hub</a> are built and published by Cardinal's CI. You can build and use local Docker images using this repository, but doing so is out of scope of this page and there is no orchestration available for it beyond running the pnpm commands yourself one by one.</p>
+  <p>The official builds that are on <a href="https://hub.docker.com/r/cardinalapps/media-server">Docker Hub</a> are built and published by Cardinal's CI. While you can definitely build and use Docker images using this repository, doing so is out of scope of this page and there is no orchestration available for it beyond running the pnpm commands yourself one by one.</p>
   <p>Running self-built containers is not offically supported, and the upstream repository may change at any time in ways that break self-build setups.</p>
 </details>
 
 <details>
   <summary>Can I use this to verify the integrity of the public builds?</summary>
-  <p>Like other CI things, this is out of scope of this page. But in short, the Media Server binary that you can build with this repository will exactly match the one that is shipped in the public Docker builds.</p>
-  <p>You can create stable and beta images as well, but the build timestamp in yours will not match the one in the official release.</p>
+  <p>Sort of? The Media Server binary that you can build with this repository will exactly match the one that is shipped in the public Docker builds.</p>
+  <p>But, like other CI things, this is out of scope of this page.</p>
+  <p>I am open to ideas on how to go about doing this sort of thing.</p>
 </details>
 
